// @NAME: Loft Language
// @TITLE: A statically-typed scripting language inspired by Rust.

// Welcome to Loft! Loft is a concise, statically-typed language designed to be
// safe and easy to embed in larger Rust projects. It is great for scripting
// game logic, configuration, data transformations, and anywhere you want a
// friendly language backed by a fast Rust runtime.
//
// These documentation pages are your guided tour — each page is also a live
// test, so every example you see has already been verified to work exactly as
// shown. The best way to get started is to read the pages in order. This first
// page introduces the handful of ideas that shape every other part of the
// language.

// ## No type declarations for local variables
// Loft figures out the type of a variable from what you assign to it.
// You never write 'let x: integer = 5' — just write 'x = 5' and move on.
// The compiler still checks types strictly; it just does the bookkeeping for you.
// If you assign the wrong type later, you get a clear compile error, not a crash.

// ## Implicit return
// The last expression in a function body is automatically its return value.
// Short helper functions need no 'return' statement, which keeps them clean.
// You can still write 'return value;' to exit early from the middle of a function.

// ## Null is visible, not hidden
// Any value can be null unless you explicitly mark it otherwise.
// Null means "no value" — like a missing search result or a failed conversion.
// A null value behaves like false in a condition, so you can test for it with '!'.
// There is no NullPointerException waiting to surprise you: null is just false.

// ## Text is UTF-8
// Text in Loft is stored as UTF-8, the same encoding used on the web.
// 'len()' counts bytes, not visible characters.
// Be mindful of multi-byte characters like emoji when slicing text by position.
// Everything from ASCII to emoji to Chinese characters works correctly.

// ## Collections share their records
// Vectors, sorted trees, and hash maps are not separate silos.
// They share their underlying storage and can be combined inside a single struct,
// so you can index the same data in multiple ways without copying anything.
// For example, a word-frequency counter can keep a vector (insertion order) and
// a hash (fast name lookup) pointing at the same records simultaneously.

// ## Hello, Loft!
// Here is a small first program to make things concrete.
// 'println' prints a line of text to standard output.
// Format strings let you embed values directly: write the variable inside '{}'.

fn main() {
    // Variables are declared by assigning a value — no 'let', 'var', or type annotation.
    // The type is inferred: greeting is text, x and y are integers.
    greeting = "Hello, Loft!";
    x = 6;
    y = 7;
    assert(x * y == 42, "Arithmetic works as you would expect");

    // Format strings use '{expression}' — you can embed any expression, not just names.
    assert("{greeting} The answer is {x * y}." == "Hello, Loft! The answer is 42.", "Format strings interpolate expressions");

    // ## Null in practice
    // Dividing by zero produces null instead of crashing.
    // In a condition, null is treated as false, so '!' turns it into true.
    // This makes it easy to handle unexpected values gracefully.
    zero = 0;
    result = 12 / zero;
    assert(!result, "Dividing by zero gives null, which is false-like");

    // ## if is an expression
    // Every 'if/else' can be used on the right side of an assignment.
    // The value of the chosen branch becomes the value of the whole expression.
    label = if x * y == 42 { "correct" } else { "wrong" };
    assert(label == "correct", "if-expression picked the right branch");

    // ## A quick taste of collections
    // A vector is an ordered list of values.
    // Fill it with a list literal using square brackets.
    // Access elements by 0-based index.
    // 'len()' tells you how many elements there are.
    scores = [10, 20, 30, 40];
    assert(scores[2] == 30, "0-based indexing: element 2 is 30");
    assert(len(scores) == 4, "len counts elements");

    total = 0;
    for s in scores { total += s; }
    assert(total == 100, "Summed all scores: {total}");
}
